fields.label: Welcome
guide: Hi, I'm ${guide}, an automated assistant.
I'm happy to show you around.  But first, may I ask how long have you been here?

fields.label: Rate Distress
guide: How are you doing emotionally right now?
How would you rate your distress? 1, not at all distressed, to 10, the highest distress you have ever felt?

fields.label: Rate Frustration
guide: How frustrated and agitated are you right now?

fields.label: Tutorial Video
guide: I'm really sorry things are so hard right now.
I would like to help as much as I can.
You may find it helpful to know a bit about what to expect today.
Watch this short video to learn more.

fields.label: Set Security Image
guide: It's really likely you will get interrupted while you're using Jaspr.
Let's set a secret image â€” like a password â€” so you can open and close the app as you need.
If you forget, a staff member can help you, too.

fields.label: Set Security Question
guide: In addition to a secret image, pick a security question and provide the answer.
This way, no one else can access the app while you're using it.

fields.label: Explore
guide: Now that I've shown you around, you can explore on your own, or I can guide you to get started.

fields.label: Jah Onboard Welcome
guide: Hi, ${guide} here. I'm glad to see you downloaded the app!

fields.label: Jah Onboard Tough Time
guide: You may be going through a difficult time right now.
My hope is that what's here in the app can help.

fields.label: Jah Onboard Show How
guide: I'll show you.

fields.label: Jah Disclaimer
guide: The app has a lot that can help in a crisis. But it's not a substitute for professional help from a doctor or therapist.
I really want you get the right help in the hardest times.
If you are in a medical emergency or contemplating acting on thoughts of suicide, call 911 or the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline (1-800-273-8255) immediately.
Does that work for you?

fields.label: Jah Onboard Glad
guide: I'm really glad you took the step to use this app and have access to these resources.

fields.label: Jah Signup Get Started
guide: Welcome to the Jaspr at Home mobile app.
Let's get started setting up your account

fields.label: Jah Signup Email And Phone
guide: First, I'll need your email and your phone number.

fields.label: Jah Signup Activation Code
guide: If we have a record of your account, you should get an activation code sent to the phone number you entered.

fields.label: Jah Signup Set Password
guide: Next, set a password.

fields.label: Jah Signup Set Device Authentication
guide: If youâ€™d like, you can use your device authentication method (FaceID, TouchID, or PIN) to access Jaspr.

fields.label: Jah Signup Done
guide: All done! Your guide will show you around the app.

fields.label: Start
guide: I'd love to work with you now to gather information so your treatment team can get you the best help.

fields.label: Drivers
guide: This interview is about drivers - the kinds of things that may directly cause many people to feel suicidal.
I know this is really private, but the more detail you can share the better your providers will be able to help you.

fields.label: Rate Psych
guide: How would you rate your psychological pain?
This is emotional pain, like anguish or misery, not physical pain or stress. Tap the number that best says how you feel right now.

fields.label: Rate Psych Text
guide: In this part, you fill in the blank to say what you find most painful.

fields.label: Rate Stress
guide: Okay, thank you. The next question asks about stress.
When you think about how you have been feeling, how would you rate your stress?
In other words how overwhelmed or pressured do you feel right now. Tap the number that best says how you feel right now.

fields.label: Rate Stress Text
guide: In the blank, please write what you are finding most stressful.

fields.label: Rate Agitation
guide: Okay, the next is about agitation.
How would you rate your agitation?
This is emotional urgency, the feeling that you need to take action. This is not irritation or annoyance.

fields.label: Rate Agitation Text
guide: Okay, thank you.
When do you most need to take action as a result of feeling agitated?

fields.label: Rate Hopeless
guide: How would you rate your hopelessness?
This is your expectation that things will not get better no matter what you do.

fields.label: Rate Hopeless Text
guide: What do you feel most hopeless about?

fields.label: Rate Self Hate
guide: How would you rate your self-hate?
This is your general feeling of disliking yourself; having no self-esteem; having no self-respect.

fields.label: Rate Self Hate Text
guide: What do you hate most about yourself?

fields.label: Rank Feelings
guide: Here are your responses to the last questions.
Can you please drag these to show the order of what's important to you (1=most important to 5=least important)?

fields.label: Suicide Risk
guide: How would you rate your overall risk of suicide?
This question means how much you want to take your life right now.
I would like to know how you honestly feel, not what you think you are supposed to say.
With 5 being you are going to take your life and 1 being you are not going to take your life, where are you right now?
fields.provider_label: Overall Risk of Suicide (1-5)

fields.label: Suicidal About Yourself
guide: How much is being suicidal related to thoughts and feelings about yourself?
fields.provider_label: Suicide related to thoughts about yourself (1-5)

fields.label: Suicidal About Others
guide: How much is being suicidal related to thoughts and feelings about others?
fields.provider_label: Suicide related to thoughts about others (1-5)

fields.label: Reasons Live Die
guide: Usually people who are suicidal have reasons for living and they also have reasons for dying. They can have both. Feeling mixed is very common.
What are your reasons for living and dying?
Write down what's important. Click done when you're finished.

fields.label: Rank Reasons Live
guide: So I can understand, can you rank these by importance?

Sometimes it can feel hard to put a number. Go with your gut feeling. When you think of your most important reason for living, which comes to mind first? Rank that first, then continue through until they are rank ordered.

fields.label: Rank Reasons Die
guide: Okay, now let's rank your reasons for dying.
Drag them to show what's most important at the top and then order the rest.

fields.label: Wish Live
guide: It's very common to have both a wish to live and a wish to die at the same time. It really helps to understand how strong each is.
Please rate the strength of your wish to live, 0 is not at all and 8 is very much wish to live.
fields.provider_label: Wish to live to the following extent (0-8)

fields.label: Wish Die
guide: Please rate the strength of your wish to die where 0 is not at all and 8 is very much wish to die.
fields.provider_label: Wish to die to the following extent (0-8)

fields.label: One Thing
guide: Now, I'd like to understand what is the one thing that could really help make you no longer feel suicidal?

By this it means one change that if it happened would really help you no longer feel suicidal. Again, use your gut - if there were one thing that would make you no longer feel suicidal what would that be?
fields.provider_label: If there were one thing that would make you no longer feel suicidal, what would that be?

fields.label: Ssf A Review
guide: Thank you for telling me how you are feeling. I know it can be hard to talk about it all.
This information really helps your providers get you the best treatment.
In the next part of the interview, I will ask you questions from a questionnaire that everybody completes.
So some of it might not apply to you. That's okay. Just answer the best you can.

fields.label: Suicidal Describe
guide: Do you have suicidal thoughts?
fields.provider_label: Do you have suicidal thoughts?

fields.label: Suicidal Freq
guide: How frequently do you think about suicide?
fields.provider_label: How frequently do you think about suicide?

fields.label: Suicidal Length
guide: When you think about suicide, how long do the thoughts last?
fields.provider_label: When you think about suicide, how long do the thoughts last?

fields.label: Worse Describe
guide: Are these thoughts about killing yourself new or worse than usual for you?
fields.provider_label: Are these thoughts about killing yourself new or worse than usual for you?

fields.label: Plans Describe
guide: Do you have a plan or plans of how you would end your life?
fields.provider_label: Do you have a plan or plans of how you would end your life?

fields.label: Means Describe
guide: Do you have access to the means to take your life? (e.g. stash of pills, guns, or any other method)
fields.provider_label: Do you have access to the means to take your life?

fields.label: Firearm Describe
guide: Do you have access to a firearm?
fields.provider_label: Do you have access to a firearm?

fields.label: Steps Describe
guide: Have you taken any steps to prepare to take your life?
(e.g. put your affairs in order, written a suicide note, or other steps)
fields.provider_label: Have you taken any steps to prepare to take your life?

fields.label: Practiced Describe
guide: Have you practiced (rehearsed) how you would take your life?
fields.provider_label: Have you practiced how you would take your life?

fields.label: Current Describe
guide: Are you here today because of a current suicide attempt?
fields.provider_label: Are you here today because of a current suicide attempt?

fields.label: Intent Describe
guide: Have you ever made an attempt to kill yourself with the intent to die?
fields.provider_label: Have you ever made an attempt to kill yourself with the intent to die?

fields.label: Times Tried Describe
guide: How many suicide attempts have you made in your lifetime?
fields.provider_label: How many suicide attempts have you made in your lifetime?

fields.label: Nssi Describe
guide: Have you ever intentionally injured yourself without intending to kill yourself?
fields.provider_label: Have you ever intentionally injured yourself without intending to kill yourself?

fields.label: Hospitalized Describe
guide: Have you ever been hospitalized for a mental health or substance use problem?
fields.provider_label: Have you ever been hospitalized for a mental health or substance use problem?

fields.label: Impulsive Describe
guide: Do you or others think you are impulsive?
fields.provider_label: o you or others think you are impulsive?

fields.label: Abuse Describe
guide: Do you or others think you have an alcohol or drug abuse problem?
fields.provider_label: Do you or others think you have an alcohol or drug abuse problem?

fields.label: Losses Describe
guide: Have you experienced a death, the loss of a job, or other losses?
fields.provider_label: Have you experienced death, the loss of a job, or other losses?

fields.label: Relationship Describe
guide: Are you having romantic and/or relationship problems?
fields.provider_label: Are you having romantic and/or relationship problems?

fields.label: Burden Describe
guide: Do you feel that others will be better off without you?
fields.provider_label: Do you feel that others will be better off without you?

fields.label: Health Describe
guide: Are you having any health or physical pain problems?
fields.provider_label: Are you having health or physical pain problems?

fields.label: Sleep Describe
guide: Are you having problems falling asleep, staying asleep, or sleeping too much?
fields.provider_label: Are you having problems falling asleep, staying asleep, or sleeping too much?

fields.label: Legal Describe
guide: Are you having any legal or financial problems?
fields.provider_label: Are you having any legal or financial problems?

fields.label: Shame Describe
guide: Are you experiencing shame about anything in your history or your current life?
fields.provider_label: Are you experiencing shame about anything in your history or your current life?

fields.label: Ssfa Finish
guide: Thank you for sharing the things that have been impacting you.
How are you doing - if you need to stretch or get a drink of water, now's a great time. When you're ready, there's another thing I'd like to help you with. I think it's the most important part.

fields.label: Make Home Start
guide: This next part is important because it can save your life.

fields.label: Surviving Makes Sense
guide: When people feel extremely upset or hopeless, they sometimes do things they wouldn't usually do.
Surviving a crisis of intense urges to take your life is like surviving other emergencies.

fields.label: I Can Help
guide: I want to help you start a plan to get through the hardest crisis times when you have intense urges to take your life.

fields.label: Desire To Harm
guide: As you might know, sometimes the desire to harm yourself can change and go up very fast.

fields.label: Skip Lethal Means
guide: That can make it dangerous to have easy access to things you'd use to harm yourself.
In your situation, might it be good to think through steps you could take to protect yourself during crises?

fields.label: Skip Reason
guide: What makes you skip for now, may I ask?

fields.label: Reason Too Tired
guide: Okay, it's totally fine if you want to rest now. Maybe you could even get a little sleep. I can wait. I'll be ready when you are.

fields.label: Reason Too Private
guide: I understand wanting to be private.
I know your providers will ask you about steps you'd be willing to take to protect yourself during a crisis.
It might be helpful if you and me prepared a little, so you know what you are and are not willing to do.
I wonder if this is a time it might be good to work together even if it's a little uncomfortable?
It might help to share what's truly troubling you. But of course, it's important you decide what's right for you.

fields.label: Reason People Will Overreact
guide: Yes, I know what you mean. Is there something specific you're afraid will happen?

fields.label: Reason People Will Overreact Take Away Means
guide: It's really normal to feel mixed about this. This is a common enough experience that actually I have a video about this topic in case you want to take a look.

Talking about means can be hard. If it helps, remember that these changes are not necessarily permanent. It's just a plan for how to protect yourself during times of intense emotion. Would you be willing to continue?

fields.label: Reason People Will Overreact Take Away Means Skip
guide: Okay, I understand. Maybe you can talk to your provider about this later.

fields.label: Reason People Will Overreact Keep Against Will
guide: I understand that worry. The best way to make sure you have a say in what happens next is to be clear about what actions you are and are not willing to take to protect yourself.
If we go through some of the ideas that have worked for other people, you may spot some things that would work for you.
Would you be willing to look at some ideas that might fit your situation?
show_if: Keep me in hospital against my will

fields.label: Reason People Will Overreact Keep Against Will Skip
guide: Okay, I understand. Maybe you can talk to your provider about this later.

fields.label: Reason Dont Want To Talk
guide: Okay. What do you worry will happen if you talk about it?
show_if: I'm not sure I want to talk about it

fields.label: Reason Dont Want To Talk All
guide: It's totally normal to feel mixed. We can look at ideas together without you committing to do any of them.
These ideas are things that other people in your situation had said are helpful.
We could start the process and you can see how you feel.
Would you be willing to look at some ideas that might fit your situation?
show_if: I'm not sure I want to talk about it

fields.label: Reason Dont Want To Talk All Skip
guide: Okay, I understand. Maybe you can talk to your provider about this later.

fields.label: Lethal Means Too Shameful
guide: Almost everybody wants to feel like they can do things on their own. It can feel humiliating to have other people know what's going on. As hard as it might be, would you consider allowing me to think with you about steps to protect your life?
Are you willing to start this section and see how it goes?
It can be really helpful to think about this as taking control of the things that will hurt you ultimately. And that's something you can take pride in.

fields.label: Lethal Means Dont Need
guide: You may well be able to do this on your own. When you're in a lot of pain, however, it's easy to slip away from your best judgment. Because of this, it's really important to have a plan around means. You just never know when you're in the moment. Are you willing to start this section and see how it goes?
show_if: I don't need to do this

fields.label: Lethal Means Get Rid
guide: There are definitely situations where you can't completely remove access to means. I have a few ideas about how to protect yourself, even in that situation, that you can look at.
Are you willing to start this section and see how it goes?

fields.label: Lethal Means Not Stable
guide: I understand.
A lot goes into deciding to stay alive. At this point, maybe we can look at ideas together, without you having to commit to anything?
show_if: Not sure I want to be stable

fields.label: Lethal Means Want To Keep
guide: Right. Many people feel more comfortable keeping access to means.

The thing about overwhelming urges to hurt yourself is they come on really quickly. People can feel impulsive when those urges hit. Maybe we could look at ways where you make your means less easy to access, just to protect yourself through this crisis?
Are you willing to start this section and see how it goes?
show_if: I want to keep my means

fields.label: Lethal Means Afraid Hospital
guide: I understand this fear. I can't say how long you'll stay in the hospital. However, not having a plan for reducing access to means can increase the risk of being hospitalized. Providers often feel more comfortable letting you go home knowing you have a realistic plan to protect yourself.
Are you willing to start this section and see how it goes?
show_if: I'm afraid this will keep me in the hospital

fields.label: Lethal Means Too Depressed
guide: I'm really glad you decided to come here and get help. What you're going through is hard.
We can do small parts together - you can take a break and go at your own pace.
Are you willing to start and see how it goes?
show_if: I feel too depressed or overwhelmed

fields.label: Consider Reducing Access
guide: For some people it's difficult to consider reducing easy access to things you'd use to harm yourself. Access can be comforting.
But removing or reducing easy access to lethal means is the most important step you can take to save your life.

fields.label: Strategies General
guide: Here are ways other people have used to protect themselves during a crisis. Can you pick strategies that might work for you?

fields.label: Additional Strategies
guide: It might help to think in detail - would any of these ideas fit your situation?
fields.provider_label: Selected strategies to protect yourself during a crisis (lethal means safety):

fields.label: Means Custom
guide: Okay, here are the ideas you picked.
This is a possible plan to talk over with your provider.
How does it look? You can add more ideas if you want.

fields.label: Means Support
guide: In your situation, can someone help you take these steps?
fields.provider_label: Can someone help you take these steps?

fields.label: Means Willing
guide: How willing are you to secure your means with the steps you just identified?
fields.provider_label: How willing are you to secure your means with the steps you identified?

fields.label: Thank You Means
guide: I appreciate that you thought about it with me. It can be a hard topic.

fields.label: Crisis Desc
guide: You might know this, but the highest urges to harm or kill yourself may last for 24-48 hours, then usually go down or go away. But in some situations, strong urges may come back.
When you think about what brought you here today, what made the urges to harm yourself go up?
fields.provider_label: When you think about what brought you here today, what made the urges to harm yourself go up?

fields.label: Get Help
guide: It's important to get help with the actual problems that drive feeling suicidal. That can take time.

fields.label: Ok Ready
guide: I'd like to walk you through some strategies for bearing the pain and surviving painful situations when you can't make things better right away.
That way you can have a plan to survive the worst moments and help you regain stability.

fields.label: Comfort And Skills
guide: To make the strongest plan, let's find a mix of things that could help when you find yourself in intense painful emotions and situations.
Let's start with the Comfort & Skills videos, activities, and music.
I definitely recommend the Paced Breathing. It's really good in a crisis.
Click on any activity you are interested in to open it. If you like something, click the heart, and I will save it for you.

fields.label: Shared Stories
guide: Now take a look at the Shared Stories. When you put a heart, I'll save it.

fields.label: View Card1
guide: Here's where I've started saving the things you liked. It will print as a card to take with you. Everything will be in the Takeaway Kit for you.

fields.label: When Things Get Hard
guide: So, when things get hard, one thing to do is watch your Jaspr videos.
Another strategy that helps a lot of people is to directly calm the body.

fields.label: Coping Body
guide: Here are ways to calm your body chemistry. Select any of what seems good to you or add your own.

fields.label: Coping Distract
guide: Sometimes it helps to get even a small mental break. What helps you distract?
Could you do an activity that holds your attention and might create positive emotions?

fields.label: Coping Help Others
guide: Could you do something that contributes or that helps someone else as a way to help yourself?

fields.label: Coping Courage
guide: Sometimes the best way to cope is to do things to help you find courage to survive and connect to your values.

fields.label: Coping Senses
guide: Sometimes in intense pain it can help to offer self-soothing and comfort through the 5 senses of seeing, smelling, hearing, touching, and tasting.

fields.label: Supportive People
guide: If possible, it's good to have a mix that includes people. Are there people who help you feel better when you're upset or who help you take your mind off things?
You don't have to tell the person you're in a crisis - sometimes just talking helps.
You can also add professionals who can help when things are bad.
fields.provider_label: Supportive People

fields.label: Coping Top
guide: Here are your ideas. In a crisis moment, which could you really do? Add the ones that would be the best strategies for you to remember to use.
fields.provider_label: Coping Strategies

fields.label: View Card2
guide: I've pulled all our work together.  I added the national lifeline because you can call or text them. It's confidential. They are 24/7 and really good.

fields.label: Reasons Live Path 2
guide: Reviewing your reasons for living can really help in a crisis.
Usually people who are suicidal have reasons for living and they also have reasons for dying. They can have both. Feeling mixed is very common.
What are your reasons for living and dying?
Write down what's important. Click done when you're finished.

fields.label: View Card3
guide: Okay, last piece! Like smoke is an early sign of fire, what cues tell you that it's time to put your plan into action?

fields.label: Warning Stressors
guide: Are there stressors and situations you might face that could increase feeling suicidal? Here's a list of common ones. Add your own too.

fields.label: Warning Thoughts
guide: Are there any internal signals that you're getting into a dangerous time?
Are certain thoughts like these a signal for you?

fields.label: Warning Feelings
guide: Do any sensations or emotions signal that you're heading into a crisis?

fields.label: Warning Actions
guide: How about actions - things you do that signal you are heading into a suicide crisis?
Here are common ones or add your own.

fields.label: Ws Top
guide: Of these, which 3 are the best signals that you are in trouble and should use your plan?
fields.provider_label: Warning Signs

fields.label: View Card4
guide: Nice work. Look it over.

fields.label: Stability Rehearsal
guide: What matters is that you feel confident the things on the plan could help you survive in the worst moment.
Try saying in your own words the main points of your plan.
For example, “When I see warning signs like (list your top 3 signals), I will _______” (list the things you will do to protect yourself and survive the crisis).
fields.provider_label: Your plan to survive the worst moments in your own words:

fields.label: Stability Confidence
guide: How confident are you in your ability to use the strategies you selected?
fields.provider_label: How confident are you in your ability to use the strategies you selected?

fields.label: Talk It Through
guide: Okay, I'll put this in the Summaries.
After you talk this through with your providers, I hope that you could share it with friends or family, if you're willing.

fields.label: Readiness
guide: People become ready to leave the emergency room in different ways and for different reasons.
How ready to leave the emergency room are you feeling?
fields.provider_label: How ready to leave the emergency room are you feeling?

fields.label: Readiness No
guide: What would make you feel more ready?
fields.provider_label: What would make you feel more ready?

fields.label: Readiness Yes Reasons
guide: What makes you feel very ready? Check all that apply.
fields.provider_label: What makes you feel very ready? Check all that apply.

fields.label: Readiness Yes Changed
guide: What has changed since you arrived at the emergency room?
fields.provider_label: What has changed since you arrived at the emergency room?

fields.label: Thanks Plan To Cope
guide: Thanks for working through this with me.
You can view your responses anytime in the 'Summaries' section at the bottom of this page.

fields.label: Walk Through
guide: That way, you can walk through them with your provider, or make edits if you need to.

fields.label: Rate Distress1
guide: I'd like to check in with you about how you're feeling after thinking all this through.
How would you rate your distress?

fields.label: Rate Frustration1
guide: How frustrated and agitated are you right now?

fields.label: Jaspr Rating
guide: Thank you for letting me know how you're feeling.
I hope I've been helpful
How would you rate the Jaspr app on a scale of 0 to 100, with 0 being the worst and 100 being the best.

fields.label: Jaspr Recommend
guide: Would you recommend the Jaspr app to other people in your situation?

fields.label: Overall Er Care
guide: How would you rate your overall experience in the emergency room?

fields.label: Give Consent for JAH
guide: Thanks for the feedback!
Would you like your own access to your crisis plan and notes from today, by creating a Jaspr Health account?

By selecting yes, Jaspr Health will keep a secure copy of your information, that you can access from your mobile phone. In future visits, you can also choose to share this information with your doctor or other healthcare providers. Your data is always in your control.

By selecting no, you will not be able to access your information in the future on your mobile device or at other healthcare providers.

fields.label: Lock Assessment
guide: I'll let your provider know you are done with the interview, okay?

fields.label: Checkin Thank You
guide: At this point, you can take a look at Comfort & Skills and videos in the Shared Stories sections.

fields.label: Will Check In
guide: I hope there's something there that can help a little bit while you're waiting.
Tap on the Jaspr logo in the top left corner to go to the Home page.

fields.label: Take Care
guide: Take good care!

fields.label: Specific Risk & Protective Factors
fields.provider_label: Specific Risk & Protective Factors

fields.label: General Risk Factors
fields.provider_label: General Risk Factors

fields.label: Making Home Safe & Stability Plan
fields.provider_label: Making Home Safe & Stability Plan

fields.label: Means Describe Review Edit
guide: Here is what you told me so far. You can add more details, if you like.

fields.label: Reasons Live Path 3
guide: Reviewing your reasons for living can really help in a crisis. Here's what you told me so far. Any edits you want to make?

fields.label: Reasons Live Path 2 Rank
guide: So I can understand, can you rank these by importance?

Sometimes it can feel hard to put a number. Go with your gut feeling. When you think of your most important reason for living, which comes to mind first? Rank that first, then continue through until they are rank ordered.

slides.text: Find your favorite videos and supportive contacts on the home page.
Hear stories from people with lived experience on the Shared Stories section.
I want to make it easier to use your stability plan. You can see your plan here.
We can walk through it step by step here in the 'Distress Survival Guide.'
Plus, some additional videos and skills for getting through difficult times.
I've put some together some contacts so they're all in one place for you.
I've also included some information about how to get the help you need from supportive people.
